R: @chamikaramj

Yeah. To clarify: I think a reasonable start will be if read() reads from
the given existing queue, and optionally (if specified) also declares the
queue, declares the exchange, and binds the queue to the exchange. Likewise
write() writes to the given existing exchange, and optionally also declares
the exchange. It writes messages of a new type RabbitMqMessage that
contains a routing key, attributes, and a payload.

This is the most general interface. We can add advanced features and
simplifications for special cases from there.
